{% raw %}<h2>The Problem</h2>

<p>React can wrap components without adding DOM elements &mdash; <code>&lt;&gt;...&lt;/&gt;</code> (Fragments), <code>Context.Provider</code>, render props, and higher-order components all compose behavior without injecting wrapper nodes. In a custom-elements framework like Web Everything, every custom element is a real DOM node. This creates problems:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>CSS layout pollution</strong> &mdash; A wrapper <code>&lt;my-provider&gt;</code> between a Flex/Grid parent and its children breaks the parent&ndash;child layout relationship</li>
  <li><strong>Semantic noise</strong> &mdash; Extra elements in the DOM that carry no semantic meaning</li>
  <li><strong>Accessibility tree bloat</strong> &mdash; Screen readers may enumerate elements that add no value</li>
  <li><strong>Selector complexity</strong> &mdash; CSS selectors must account for intermediate wrappers (<code>.parent > my-provider > .child</code>)</li>
</ul>

<p>This research catalogs every pattern and runtime solution available, evaluates what Web Everything already implements, and identifies the remaining gaps.</p>


