<h2>The Primary Gap: DOM-Less Context Providers</h2>

<p>Web Everything already covers most DOM-less composition patterns. The one significant gap is <strong>context/injector providers that do not affect CSS layout</strong>.</p>

<p>The injector chain walks the DOM tree &mdash; providers must be DOM nodes. React's <code>&lt;Context.Provider&gt;</code> adds zero DOM because React has a virtual tree. In Web Everything, providing context requires a real element in the DOM hierarchy.</p>

<h3>Proposed Solution: <code>display: contents</code> Custom Elements</h3>

<p>A custom element with <code>display: contents</code> achieves both goals:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Participates in injector chain</strong> &mdash; it is a real DOM node, so <code>InjectorRoot.getProviderOf()</code> walks through it</li>
  <li><strong>Invisible to CSS layout</strong> &mdash; its children become direct flex/grid items of the grandparent</li>
  <li><strong>Events still work</strong> &mdash; the element receives and dispatches events normally</li>
  <li><strong>Selectors still work</strong> &mdash; <code>querySelector</code>, <code>closest()</code> can find it</li>
</ul>

<p>Example:</p>
<we-code-view><pre><code>&lt;!-- This provider is layout-transparent --&gt;
&lt;context-provider style="display:contents" heading-level="3"&gt;
  &lt;auto-heading&gt;Title&lt;/auto-heading&gt;  &lt;!-- resolves to h3 --&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;Content&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/context-provider&gt;</code></pre></we-code-view>

<p><strong>Accessibility note:</strong> As of 2023&ndash;2024, <code>display: contents</code> accessibility bugs have been largely fixed in major browsers. The element remains in the accessibility tree. However, it should not be used on inherently semantic elements like <code>&lt;button&gt;</code>, <code>&lt;table&gt;</code>, or <code>&lt;details&gt;</code>.</p>


<h2>Secondary Opportunity: Functional Components in JSXRenderer</h2>

<p>The existing JSXRenderer supports string tags and class constructors. Extending it to support <strong>function components</strong> would enable Stencil/Haunted-style DOM-less composition:</p>

<we-code-view><pre><code>// Function component &mdash; no custom element, no wrapper
const List = ({ items }) =&gt; (
  &lt;&gt;
    {items.map(item =&gt; &lt;li&gt;{item}&lt;/li&gt;)}
  &lt;/&gt;
);

// Usage &mdash; List adds zero DOM nodes
const el = &lt;ul&gt;&lt;List items={['a', 'b', 'c']} /&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;;</code></pre></we-code-view>

<p>When <code>type</code> is a function (not a class constructor), <code>createElement</code> calls it with props and inlines the returned DOM. Zero extra elements. Zero custom element registration.</p>


<h2>What Web Everything Already Has</h2>

<p>The framework already implements the strongest set of DOM-less composition mechanisms available to a custom-elements-based framework:</p>

<ol>
  <li><strong>Comment markers</strong> for structural directives (no layout impact)</li>
  <li><strong>TransientElement</strong> for dynamic tag resolution (element vanishes after replacement)</li>
  <li><strong>DocumentFragment</strong> for grouping during creation (dissolves on insertion)</li>
  <li><strong>CustomAttribute</strong> for behavioral composition (zero DOM)</li>
  <li><strong>Mixins</strong> for class-level composition (zero DOM)</li>
  <li><strong>JSX Fragment</strong> via JSXRenderer (DocumentFragment-based)</li>
  <li><strong>Customized built-in elements</strong> via <code>is</code> attribute (no wrapper)</li>
</ol>


<h2>Recommendations (Ranked)</h2>

<h3>Tier 1: Already Validated &mdash; Continue Investing</h3>
<ol>
  <li><strong>Comment-based virtual elements</strong> &mdash; Primary pattern. Proven by Angular, Solid, Lit, and now Web Everything.</li>
  <li><strong>TransientElement</strong> &mdash; Unique to WE. AutoHeading proves the pattern.</li>
  <li><strong>DocumentFragment</strong> &mdash; Standard. Already used for JSX and template stamping.</li>
</ol>

<h3>Tier 2: High-Value Additions</h3>
<ol start="4">
  <li><strong><code>display: contents</code> provider elements</strong> &mdash; Solves the context provider layout problem. Enables React-like <code>Context.Provider</code> without virtual DOM.</li>
  <li><strong>Functional components in JSXRenderer</strong> &mdash; Small change (detect function type in createElement), large impact for composition.</li>
  <li><strong>Transient-to-comments bridge</strong> &mdash; Generalize TransientElement to replace itself with comment markers (not just native elements), unifying the transient and virtual element patterns.</li>
</ol>

<h3>Tier 3: Worth Considering</h3>
<ol start="7">
  <li><strong>Proxy-based reactive providers</strong> &mdash; For stores/contexts that do not need DOM presence.</li>
  <li><strong>DOM Parts adoption path</strong> &mdash; When the W3C DOM Parts proposal matures, it would standardize comment-based markers. The framework is already positioned for this transition.</li>
</ol>


<h2>Open Questions</h2>

<ol>
  <li>Should <code>display: contents</code> be the default for injector-only elements, or should it be opt-in via an attribute?</li>
  <li>Should functional components in JSXRenderer support hooks (useState, useEffect) like Haunted, or remain pure render functions?</li>
  <li>When TransientElement replaces itself with comments (transient-to-comments bridge), how should the comment lifecycle callbacks wire up to the original element's logic?</li>
  <li>Should the framework provide a <code>&lt;provider&gt;</code> custom element out of the box, or let users create their own <code>display: contents</code> elements?</li>
</ol>


<h2 id="composition-guide">Dev guide: which mechanism, and why</h2>

<p>The catalog above surveys <em>every</em> pattern. This section is the <strong>decision guide</strong> ratified under
<a href="/backlog/1963-composition-rubric-re-judged-to-framework-parity-strict-per-/">#1963</a>: the menu you actually pick
from, with pros, cons and when-to-use, plus the questions every developer asks &mdash; <em>why not <code>is=</code>?</em>,
<em>directive or behaviour?</em>, <em>transient or persistent?</em> The rule of thumb up top: <strong>reach for a behaviour
first, a directive only for region/pre-connection control, and emit a real native element for a presentational leaf.</strong></p>

<h3>Two angles: dev freedom vs the standard's fixed floor</h3>

<p>Read every ruling below through one of two lenses. As an <strong>app developer</strong> you get the full menu and
maximum freedom &mdash; the standard constrains only a small fixed floor. As an implementor of the <strong>block
standard</strong>, the same surface partitions into what is forced vs what is a per-project option:</p>

<we-data-table>
<table class="data-table">
  <thead>
    <tr><th>Tier</th><th>Who decides</th><th>Covers</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>FIXED</strong></td>
      <td>The standard forces it</td>
      <td>The 5-point acceptance bar; the budgeted-host-node spine; the per-layer native/plug partition; irreplaceable-native blocks (real inputs/pickers) <strong>must emit native</strong>; the statute bars &mdash; no load-bearing <code>is=</code>, the single-substrate floor, MaaS serves only platform-correct variants.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>CONFIGURABLE</strong></td>
      <td>Per-project option &mdash; platform-correct variants only</td>
      <td>Transient &harr; persistent light-DOM for <em>soft / replicable</em> blocks (badge, tag, card, button, chip); the leaf default (<a href="/backlog/1962-leaf-default-transient-vs-persistent-the-mechanism-rule-for/">#1962</a>); which sanctioned variant the configurator / MaaS assembles. Native-first is the <strong>default</strong>, the alternative an <strong>opt-in</strong>. A substrate swap (a load-bearing non-standard shim) is <em>never</em> configurable.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>FREEDOM</strong></td>
      <td>The dev's call</td>
      <td>Which mechanism per case, from the menu below. The standard gates only the FIXED floor; everything else is yours.</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>
</we-data-table>

<p>So <strong>dev-freedom = CONFIGURABLE + FREEDOM</strong>, sitting on top of the non-negotiable FIXED native-first floor.</p>

<h3>The mechanism menu (pros, cons, when to use)</h3>

<we-data-table>
