<h3>Worked example: directive vs behaviour</h3>

<p>The single most-asked design question. <strong>Behaviour is first-choice</strong> because a behaviour attaches
<em>after</em> its element connects &mdash; it can decorate but it cannot prevent or multiply that connection. Only a
directive, sitting as a comment <em>before</em> the element exists, can gate or repeat it. So the test is:
<em>do you need to control whether/how-many-times an element connects, or transform a region before it upgrades?</em>
Yes &rarr; directive. No &rarr; behaviour.</p>

<p><strong>Behaviour</strong> &mdash; enhance an element that already connected (the default):</p>
<we-code-view><pre><code>&lt;!-- decorate a connected element in place; zero extra nodes --&gt;
&lt;a href="/report.pdf" download-progress&gt;Download report&lt;/a&gt;

class DownloadProgress extends CustomAttribute {
  connectedCallback() { /* the &lt;a&gt; already exists &mdash; wire progress UI onto it */ }
}</code></pre></we-code-view>

<p><strong>Directive</strong> &mdash; region / pre-connection control, the two canonical cases:</p>
<we-code-view><pre><code>&lt;!-- ViewIf: gate WHETHER the element connects at all --&gt;
&lt;!-- control:if when="loggedIn" --&gt;
  &lt;a href="/account"&gt;Account&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;!-- /control:if --&gt;

&lt;!-- ForEach: control HOW MANY TIMES &mdash; keyed siblings, no wrapper element --&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
  &lt;!-- control:for-each items="members" --&gt;
    &lt;li class="member"&gt;${item.name}&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;!-- /control:for-each --&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;</code></pre></we-code-view>

<p>A behaviour could never write either of these: by the time <code>connectedCallback</code> runs, the element has
already connected once &mdash; too late to suppress it (<code>ViewIf</code>) or to fan it out (<code>ForEach</code>).</p>

<h3>FAQ: why not <code>is=</code>?</h3>

<p><code>is=</code> (customized built-in elements) looks attractive &mdash; <code>&lt;button is="my-button"&gt;</code> upgrades a
real native element with zero wrapper. <strong>It is not a WE mechanism.</strong> Every job <code>is=</code> could do is
dominated by a mechanism that is cross-browser and single-substrate:</p>

<we-data-table>
<table class="data-table">
  <thead>
    <tr><th>The job</th><th>Use this instead</th><th>Why it dominates <code>is=</code></th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td>Load-bearing native output (a real button/link/heading)</td>
      <td><strong>Transient</strong> (emit-to-native)</td>
      <td>You get the genuine native element with no upgrade step and no polyfill &mdash; full parity, every browser.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Behaviour on an authored element</td>
      <td><strong><code>CustomAttribute</code></strong></td>
      <td>In-place, cross-browser, single-substrate &mdash; beats <code>is=</code> on every axis, and Safari never ships <code>is=</code> for autonomous-equivalent needs.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>A persistent live instance</td>
      <td><strong>Persistent light-DOM CE</strong> (family B)</td>
      <td>A durable host you actually own, with <code>ElementInternals</code> &mdash; not a borrowed native tag.</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>
</we-data-table>

<p>Because every job is dominated, <code>is=</code> is never a block mechanism and never a default. WE documents it
<strong>only as an explicit opt-in developer option</strong> (a polyfill in Frontier UI, lower-compliance, on the §7
spectrum) &mdash; for a developer who knowingly wants it, never as something the standard reaches for.</p>

<h3>FAQ: <code>is=</code> vs transient &mdash; aren't they the same?</h3>

<p>No, and the distinction is the reason transient wins. <strong><code>is=</code> upgrades an <em>existing</em> native element
in place</strong> &mdash; one substrate, but it depends on a browser feature Safari refuses and so needs a load-bearing
polyfill. <strong>Transient is broader</strong>: a custom element that replaces <em>itself</em> with native output. That
breadth is the point &mdash; transient is <strong>multi-root</strong> (it can emit a fragment or a comment-pair, not just a
single tag), <strong>polymorphic</strong> (it resolves <em>which</em> native element at runtime &mdash; <code>AutoHeading</code>
becoming the right <code>h1&hellip;h6</code>), and rides a <strong>single substrate</strong> with no non-standard shim. <code>is=</code>
is the narrow, shim-dependent special case; transient is the general, standard-aligned mechanism that subsumes it.</p>


<h3>The acceptance bar (what every choice is judged against)</h3>

<p>Whichever mechanism you pick, #1963 grades it against a five-point, zero-compromise bar &mdash; a native-first system
that can't match framework composition DX never wins first-level adoption:</p>

<ol>
  <li><strong>Ergonomics &ge; frameworks</strong> &mdash; DX competitive with React/Vue/Svelte/Solid, not merely "good for web components."</li>
  <li><strong>Zero compromise</strong> &mdash; no breakage of layout (flex/grid direct-child), CSS (selector/cascade) or accessibility (AX tree + content model).</li>
  <li><strong>A no-compromise solution for <em>every</em> case</strong> &mdash; an uncovered case becomes a build item, never a tolerated gap.</li>
  <li><strong>Open to net-new mechanisms</strong> &mdash; where nothing clears the bar, invent a plug (a proposed standard), authored to deprecate + migrate when the native standard ships.</li>
  <li><strong>Authoring-surface-agnostic</strong> &mdash; clean in plain HTML (declarative/SSR) <em>and</em> JSX.</li>
</ol>

<p>Today cases 4/5 (if/for/switch) and 7 (behaviours) are at parity; cases 2, 3, 6 and 9 are at parity pending a named
confirm; case 1 routes to <a href="/backlog/1962-leaf-default-transient-vs-persistent-the-mechanism-rule-for/">#1962</a>;
case 8 (the <code>is=</code> jobs) is covered. The one honest open gap is <strong>case 10 &mdash; deep <em>structural</em>
nesting in declarative HTML</strong>, where the platform reaches only cheap-node (not zero-node) composition; that residual
is a tracked build under #1963, not something the menu above papers over.</p>
